Swarm secrets and configs.

From notebook eight, remember the idea of secrets as files rather than environment variables. In swarm they become a first-class object, stored encrypted at rest in the cluster's replicated state. You create a secret by feeding its value in, then list secrets and inspect them, though inspecting only shows metadata and never returns the value itself.

You attach a secret to a service, and inside the container the value appears as a file at a known path, owned by root with restrictive permissions, with the app reading from that file. Crucially, only the nodes actually running a task for that service ever receive the secret. Managers do not push secrets out to nodes that do not need them, which keeps the blast radius small. Configs are exactly the same idea but for non-secret configuration files, distributed to every node running a task and mounted at a target path, which is perfect for something like a web-server configuration file.

Both secrets and configs are immutable by design. To change a value, you create a new object with a new name and update the service to reference it. That is not an inconvenience so much as a feature, because rolling out a configuration change becomes a service update, which means it inherits all the rolling-update guarantees, gradual rollout, health monitoring, and automatic rollback on failure. So a configuration change is deployed with the same care and safety as a code change.
